<font color="#FF0000">CORPSMEN, A GRUNTS HERO</font><br>
<tt>Fri Nov 21  4:24:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc had it the toughest of all I truly believe, the anger we felt toward the NVA/VC we could vent by returning fire, make them pay for the pain... we could do something about it, many of the corpsmen would not pick up a M16 even to defend themselfs. The bravest and sometimes the most foolish men I have ever known. They have my total un-dying respect if they would fight back or not. To be on that battle feild sh*t flying everywhere and doing whatever it took to save lives ignoring the danger to their own. I wish there was a monmument somewhere for ALL of them, they gave so much in THE WORST of all possible conditions. Anytime Doc got his ass out in the open to drag someone back not only did we open up with everything to protect him... got my ass in a sling cause I would jump up to help... as well as others would jump in. Doc always got the can of peachs.. he deserved more, but that was all we had to give.<br><br>
To ALL Corps men out there, you are the grunts hero.. 'cause of you guys a LOT of us are alive today because of you. I doubt if any one would argue that you guys where/are the bravest and best of the American armed forces has to offer.<br>
Thank's guys....<br><br>
Reg: a little too close:<br>
  It had to be, very close just save people... Just one of those days when it's too close to call and just do it. How that F4 drive laid it in there with that percision at that speed is beyond me... <br><br>
OD.....
